en $\\left|\\frac{dB}{dt}\\right|$ is maximized and use this maximal value (constant during the muon's transit for this calculation).\\n\\nThe muon experiences a net force in the azimuthal direction due to $E_{\\varphi}$ and soon after, a steady-state drift speed relative to the fluid due to this electric field, opposed by a Stokes drag force: \\[ F_\\mathrm{drag} = 6 \\pi \\eta r_\\mu v_\\mathrm{drift}, \\] where $r_\\mu = 1.15 \\times 10^{-18}\\ \\mathrm{m}$ is an effective interaction radius. No net magnetic (Lorentz) force acts axially since the drift is strictly azimuthal and $\\vec{B}$ is perpendicular to $\\vec{v}_\\mathrm{drift}$. Assume the muon quickly reaches this steady-state drift and that random thermal motion and all other forces are negligible.\\n\\nBecause the pipe is axially aligned with the train's motion, any azimuthal drift does not contribute to forward progress along the pipe axis. Thus, the muon's velocity along the pipe (in the train frame) is strictly the fluid velocity $v_f$ due to the pressure differential (from Poiseuille's law), and not its azimuthal drift.\\n\\nLet $L$ be the Lorentz-contracted length of the pipe as seen in the ground frame. Compute the probability $P$ that the muon, starting at the pipe entrance in the ground frame, exits the pipe before decaying. Take all relevant relativistic effects into account:\\n\\n- Use the time dilation formula in the ground frame for the muon, i.e., its mean proper lifetime is $\\tau_0$, but in the ground frame its decay lifetime is $\\tau = \\gamma_\\mu\\, \\tau_0$, where $\\gamma_\\mu$ is evaluated using the muon's velocity $v_{\\mu,\\mathrm{ground}}$ (as explained below).\\n- Use the correct Lorentz velocity addition (collinear case) to compute the muon's velocity in the ground frame (along the pipe), given its velocity $v_f$ inside the moving train ($v$).\\n\\nExplicitly:\\n\\n1. Calculate the mean fluid velocity $v_f$ (train frame) using Poiseuille's law:\\n\\[ v_f = \\frac{\\Delta P\\, R^2}{8 \\eta L_p} \\]\\n2. The muon's velocity in the train frame is $v_f$ (along the axis). In the ground frame, the pipe moves at $v$; thus, the muon's ground-frame axial velocity is:\\n\\[ v_{\\mu,\\mathrm{ground}} = \\frac{v + v_f}{1 + \\frac{v v_f}{c^2}} \\]\\n3. The Lorentz-contracted length of the pipe as observed in the ground frame is:\\n\\[ L = \\frac{L_0}{\\gamma_{\\rm train}}, \\quad \\text{where}~\\gamma_{\\rm train} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}} \\],\\n\\n4. The transit time for the muon in the ground frame to traverse the contracted pipe is $t_{\\rm transit} = L / v_{\\mu,\\mathrm{ground}}$.\\n\\n5. The muon's survival probability upon exiting the pipe is then:\\n\\[ P = \\exp\\left(-\\frac{t_{\\rm transit}}{\\tau}\\right) \\]\\n\\nwith $\\tau = \\gamma_\\mu \\tau_0$, $\\gamma_\\mu = 1/\\sqrt{1 - v_{\\mu,\\mathrm{ground}}^2/c^2}$.\\n\\n\\textbf{Given all data above, compute numerically (to three significant digits)} the probability $P$ (dimensionless) that the muon survives to reach the front of the moving pipe, starting from rest in the ground frame at the pipe entrance as described. Give your answer as $\\boxed{P~\\text{(dimensionless)}}$.",
